  "doc_id": "49540",
  "text": "While the specific attributes of the requirement are broadly defined, CHHS students, given their interest in the health professions, are especially attracted to the service learning component of study abroad. A few researchers have examined the effects of participating in international service learning activities [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Participants showed gains in the following areas: cultural awareness; understanding of social justice issues; motivation to pursue future service activities; and enhanced clarity vis-à-vis career path. All of the studies underscore the importance of student involvement in the process, flexible and involved faculty, and the use of curriculum that ties classroom learning to the field.",
